  "firstDescriptionArticle": "Choć technologia pływającej fotowoltaiki (floating PV) jest bardziej w fazie początkowego rozwoju niż rozkwitu, to ma przed sobą dobre perspektywy. Wynika to głównie z ograniczonej dostępności terenów, na których można instalować tradycyjne panele solarne. Potencjał i doświadczenia sektora floating PV przedstawia w swoim raporcie organizacja Solar Power Europe. \n\nSkatalogowanie najlepszych praktyk i zgromadzenie specjalistycznej wiedzy dotyczącej pływającej fotowoltaiki to główny cel raportu przygotowanego przez Solar Power Europe (SPE). Organizacja wskazuje, że pływające instalacje fotowoltaiczne zaczynają się pojawiać na całym świecie – od kilku lat działają w Azji i Europie. Jednak kryzysy klimatyczne przy rosnącej konkurencji o grunty spowodują przyspieszenie zastosowania tej technologii.\n\nJak podkreśla SPE, wszystkie strony zainteresowane rozwojem floating PV (FPV) – od deweloperów przez organy publiczne po społeczności lokalne – powinny mieć dostęp do wiedzy, doświadczeń i studiów przypadku w zakresie pływającej fotowoltaiki. Realizacja projektów fotowoltaicznych na wodzie – zarówno na zbiornikach lądowych, jak i morskich – wymaga bowiem odpowiedniego dostosowania technicznego w zestawieniu z tradycyjną fotowoltaiką, zarówno na etapie projektowania, jak i budowy oraz eksploatacji elektrowni PV. Źródłem informacji na ten temat ma być właśnie przygotowany przez SPE pierwszy „podręcznik” o floating PV.",
  "secondDescriptionArticle": "A Chinese manufacturer has set a new record for the efficiency of a photovoltaic cell made of silicon. In doing so, it has improved on its record set a year earlier.\n\nIn November 2022, Chinese photovoltaic cell and panel manufacturer LONGi announced that it had achieved an efficiency record for a full-size, multi-junction HJT cell. On the Chinese manufacturer's full-size cell, the German institute ISFH measured an efficiency of 26.81 percent. At the time, this was a global record for the efficiency of a cell made of silicon, and no better result had been achieved on a full-size silicon PV cell for more than a year.\n\nNow the Chinese manufacturer has improved on its achievement from late 2022. An efficiency of 27.09 percent was measured on a silicon cell supplied by LONGi, a result that was to be achieved in tests performed again by ISFH. The record-breaking cell was made using a technology referred to as HBC (Heterojunction Back Contact).",
  "thirdDescriptionArticle": "The prevailing weather conditions over the holidays were conducive to high wind power production. However, the operation of some wind power plants was reduced at the behest of the Polish Power Grid, which once again had to manage the surplus energy in the National Power System over the holidays.\n\nOn December 25 in the afternoon, the total power with which wind farms in Poland were operating exceeded even 8.2 GW and was close to a record. With similar power, windmills also worked the next day in the afternoon. On the first and second days of the holidays, photovoltaic power plants also provided additional power during the midday hours. They worked - despite considerable cloud cover - with a power output exceeding even 2 GW (in addition, generation from some PV installations was consumed immediately \"behind the meter\" in the homes of prosumers).\n\nDue to the high production and the holiday drop in energy demand, the Polish Power Grid (PSE) decided to reduce generation from some generation sources and had to launch emergency power exports to neighboring countries.",
  "fourthDescriptionArticle": "According to preliminary data from PSE, ARE and ENTSOE, analyzed by WysokieNapiecie.pl, Poland produced nearly 166 TWh of electricity in 2023. Of this, as much as 44 TWh came from renewable energy sources, half of which were supplied by onshore wind farms.\n\nThe share of coal in Poland's electricity production in 2023 fell to 63%, the share of renewables rose to 27%, and the share of gas reached 10%. While the share of gas remains at the level we already saw in 2020, coal and renewables showed the fastest changes ever. Renewable energy sources increased their share of the country's energy mix from 20% to 27% within a year, while coal's share shrank from 73% to 63%, reaching the lowest level in the more than 100-year history of Poland's electric power industry. This is the rate assumed in the latest (created after Russia's aggression against Ukraine and the outbreak of the Russia-EU fuel war), scenario of the Ministry of Climate and Environment. Indeed, the update to Poland's Energy Policy, which is being prepared, assumes that over the next decade the share of coal will fall further at a similar rate, up to less than 20% in 2035."
